Somethign I suggested a long time ago was the idea of an offensive damage shield. Rather than casting a DS on the MA so that every time they get hit, damage is caused, but one that every time they hit they do more damage. This would be separate from weapon damage calculation. Just flat replace Okiels with these. Use the same times, etc.l. as the okiels line and make them stack with all DSs. 2 points a hit is actually pretty damn good -- and 6 is even better. at higher levels make group versions, and maybe a level 64ish AE version. This is definately a buff, but it's the kind that is right along the lines we intend -- damage output.<br>
<br>
Second change I would like to see is a set of spells where they do damage like a damage over time, but are a &quot;holding damage&quot; type spell. Here is what I mean. I cast a draught on a mob, and it lands. Initially it does some damage, but so long as I take no other action (move, cast, etc...) the damage keeps going. Imagine casting an electrical stream on a mob, and it keeps hitting it. As we hold it, mana keeps getting eaten, the longer it's held, the less mana over time it uses and the more agro it generates. The initial damage would be on the order of a drought, maybe 2.8-3.2 to 1, and then 4 to 1 after that.<br>
<br>
Last change would be for more powerful push spells. Thunderstrike like spells, but with bigger pushes and more damage. I mean sutff that knocks a mob hundreds of feet across a zone. Stick a 1 second stun on it, or better a root component when it's cast. Mana heavy, but fast casting. <br>
<br>
Here are my arguements overall: They add to groupability, and add some pretty nify raid abilities in certain situations. The offensive damage shield is really the ringer I think. There are a lot of ways to keep power in check with these. Useing elemental saves, and making some higher level version Lure-like, for example. <br>
<br>
